instance dt_constellation : DTDFVocab:Constellation [
    base:desc "The system is orchestrated using a Model‑Based Systems Engineering (MBSE) approach. The component and connector structure is described in SysML via an Architecture Design Block Diagram (Fig. 3). Behavioural dynamics are captured in executable MATLAB/Simulink models which are linked to the SysML model. The twin’s architecture follows a hierarchical multi‑level abstraction (requirements, functional, logical, product) with a centralised model repository. Coordination between the structural and behavioural models is achieved through model integration within the MBSE toolchain, enabling automatic generation of simulation and code artifacts."
]

instance life_cycle_stages : DTDFVocab:EvolutionStage [
    base:desc "The digital twin lifecycle is built on four stacked abstraction layers: a requirements layer that captures system constraints, a functional architecture layer that defines high‑level capabilities, a logical architecture layer that describes component interactions, and a product/technical layer that specifies concrete implementation details."
]

instance fidelity_and_validity_considerations : DTDFVocab:FidelityConsideration [
    base:desc "A robust fidelity and validity protocol balances analytical simplicity with realistic dynamics. The twin employs a multi‑resolution modeling hierarchy: lower‑order kinematics models for rapid controller tuning, and higher‑order dynamic models that incorporate detailed motor electrical characteristics, gearbox backlash, and nonlinear friction. Validation is performed by systematic comparison of simulated joint trajectories against measured data collected during a calibration routine. The deviation metric employs the mean absolute deviation over a five‑second test step, with a threshold of <0.05 degrees for position and <0.3 degrees per second for velocity. Exceedances trigger a re‑parameterization loop where parameters are adjusted via a gradient‑based optimizer. Uncertainty quantification is performed through Monte‑Carlo simulation of sensor noise and component tolerances, yielding confidence intervals for predicted states. Error detection is integrated at both data and model levels: outlier filtering removes transient spikes, while residual analysis flags model mismatch when the difference between predicted and measured signals exceeds three sigma. Quality assurance is maintained through automated regression tests that run on every code and model revision, generating a signed “fit report” that documents validation status, test coverage, and any identified regressions."
]

instance horizontal_integration : DTDFVocab:HoriIntegration [
    base:desc "The Digital Shadow is a passive one‑way data consumer; it receives data streams from the physical object without pushing data back. The integration is limited to a single data flow channel; no bidirectional communication or external enterprise system integration (e.g., MES/ERP) is described. Inter‑system protocols are not specified beyond the generic one‑way data ingestion."
]
